Analysis of white wine quality

In this exploratory data analysis study, white wine Quality is discussed.The dataset used in this investigation is ‘White Wine Quality’, which is a part of two datasets for white wine and red whine. Following is the reference for the dataset.

  • P. Cortez, A. Cerdeira, F. Almeida, T. Matos and J. Reis. Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties. In Decision Support Systems, Elsevier, 47(4):547-553. ISSN: 0167-9236.

Information about dataset

In the dataset, there are over 4800 records are available in 11 attributes. Most of the attributes are the chemical and physical properties of the wine type.

The dataset contains following attributes.

##  [1] "X"                    "fixed.acidity"        "volatile.acidity"    
##  [4] "citric.acid"          "residual.sugar"       "chlorides"           
##  [7] "free.sulfur.dioxide"  "total.sulfur.dioxide" "density"             
## [10] "pH"                   "sulphates"            "alcohol"             
## [13] "quality"

The size of the dataset is as follows.

## [1] 4898   13

Based on the reference of the dataset, the following descriptions are given for the attributes in the dataset. The corresponding units if any for the atributes are also given in along with the atribute name.

fixed acidity (g/dm^3):

  • Most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily).

volatile acidity (g/dm^3):

  • The amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste

citric acid (g/dm^3):

  • Found in small quantities, citric acid can add ‘freshness’ and flavor to wines

residual sugar (g/dm^3):

  • The amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, it’s rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet

chlorides (g/dm^3):

  • The amount of salt in the wine

free sulfur dioxide (g/dm^3):

  • The free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine

total sulfur dioxide (g/dm^3):

  • Amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine

density (g/cm^3):

  • The density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content

pH: * Describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale

sulphates (g/dm^3):

  • A wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant

alcohol (% by volume):

  • The percent alcohol content of the wine

quality:

  • Score between 0 and 10

All the atributes in the dataset are numerical. However, The quality attribute was factorized, because the quality atribute is used to rank the qualty.

Univariate Analysis

Based on the above grid of histograms and barchart, it is obvious that all the measured parameters for white wine are more or less normally distributed except ‘residual sugar’ which is left skewed. The distribution of pH is perfect normal distribution.

Based on the above summary statistics, some outlier like data points can be observed specially for the atributes - residual.sugar, free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide. In this three atributes, the maximum value are significantly higher than the corresponding third quartile. However, to veryfy whether these max pointes are outlieers or not, a detailed analysis are required. Also, the stitistcs show that the majority of white wines fall into 5 and 6 quality categories.

Bivariate Plots Section

From the univariant analysis in the above section reflects some insights of individual atributes in the dataset. In this section correlations between the atributes are investigated.

In order to understand the relationships between the atributes, following coorellation plots matrixs was generated. The matrix of plots are advantageous, because, all the relationships if any can be eaily identified. Therefore, further analysis can be easily implemented.

In the above matrix of plots, scatter plots were shown each atributes to others at the lower part of the diogonal. I the upper part, the corresponding correlation coefficients are shown. Along the diogonal the density plots are displayed for each atribute.

Bivariate Analysis

When examine the correlation coeffient for each relationship, some of the atributes seems to be high to moderately coorelated each other. For example, corellation coefficients of, alcohol vs density, residual.sugar vs density, total .sulfur.dioxide vs density, total.sulfur.dioxide vs free.sulfur.dioxide are -0.78, 0.84, 0.53 and 0.62, repectively.

Let’s look at each relationship seperately.

The data distribution in above plots shows faily good correlations with R^2 > 0.5.

As noticed in the univarient analysis in the previous section, there seems to be a few outliers observable in the datset. Generally, in standaed conditions the density of water is 1.00 g/cm^3. Therefore, the density of a solution in which water is the solvent, should be slightly less than 1.00 g/cm^3. In the above plots we can observe two density values greater tahn 1.00 g/cm^3. Therefore, we can remove those outliers from the dataset. Folowing plots were generated without the density outliers. Also, extreame valus for sulfur dioxides can be removed.
